To do this, we need to compute the pushforward of the complement map. The key insight is that the complement of a binomial graph is also binomial, with parameter `σ p`. 

Let's compute the pushforward:
- The original graph `G` has law `binomialRandom V p`. So, `G` is the image of `Ber(diagSetᶜ, p)` under `edgeSet`.
- The complement graph `Gᶜ` is the image of `fun ω ↦ (G ω)ᶜ` under the same space.
- The map `fun ω ↦ (G ω)ᶜ` is the composition of `fun x ↦ xᶜ` and `G`.
- Since `G` is `binomialRandom V p`, `Gᶜ` will be `binomialRandom V (σ p)`. 

This is because the complement of a Bernoulli `Ber(p)` is `Ber(σ p)`, and applying a map to a random variable preserves the probability measure.

